headline: CNN This Morning
subHeadline: February Jobs Numbers; Hollywood's Biggest Night This Weekend; Daylight Saving Time Change This Weekend. Aired 8:30-9a ET

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: This has an immediate effect on everything, right? You, our lives, everything. Just in, the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics just announcing how many jobs were added to the economy in February.Christine Romans here with the number. So, is this -

utterances.speaker: CHRISTINE ROMANS, CNN CHIEF BUSINESS CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: A lot of hiring.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Is this good or bad?

utterances.speaker: KAITLAN COLLINS, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: So, it's good for employees. Bad for employers. Bad for the Fed.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: Yes. COLLINS

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: So, a good economy could eventually be bad news for Americans because it means the Fed has to continue to raise interest rates. You've got wages up 4.6 percent. That's great. I mean people's paychecks are unequivocally bigger. But it's feeding into the inflation story. And so the Fed thinks that inflation staying too high is more dangerous than maybe trying to cool off the job market a little bit.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: So --

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: I know, it's upside down.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Well, it's weird because everybody I talk to - and this -- just yesterday I was having breakfast with a bunch of folks and they said, Don, we're so confused when you guys talk about the economy -

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: And you get the new jobs numbers and the stock market, whatever, everything's going gangbusters, but yet it's bad. How - what do I -- I don't know what to say to them.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: You know, it's interesting because we kind of broke all of the models after Covid and so we're trying -- we have a very confusing picture of the economy. The underlying strength of the economy over the past six weeks has been undeniable. The consumer, retail sales, the job market, and inflation is still too high. All of this is a function of a - of a strong recovery in the economy.And while that is good news, it feels like good news, if it feeds into inflation and inflation gets entrenched, then that slows growth, and then that can cause a recession.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: And the question -- everyone who's paying close attention to this, not just us, it's the White House. Our senior White House correspondent MJ Lee is on the lawn.MJ, obviously, they are always looking closely to this. You reported they were looking for this goldilocks number. It got a lot higher than goldilocks. It's way more than expected. What's the reaction you're hearing so far?

utterances.speaker: MJ LEE, CNN SENIOR WHITE HOUSE CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: Yes, Katelin, you know the number that White House officials had really been hoping to see was something in the mid 200s. So, you're right that this is a little bit bigger than that. But I can - I suspect that they are going to be pretty pleased with this.You know, that goldilocks number that we talk about, they wanted something that wasn't too big, like what we saw in the month of January when the economy added more than 500,000 jobs. That was, frankly, shocking to a lot of economists. But they, obviously, also always want to see strength and robustness in the jobs market. And so much of this has to do with being on Federal Reserve watch. They knew and very much took note inside the building behind me when Jerome Powell said in recent days and suggested that if there are more indicators that the jobs market is just too hot, that the labor market is too hot, that, yes, the central bank could bring back more aggressive interest rate hikes. That's not something that the White House wants to see. But at the same time, this has almost sort of been a good problem for the White House to have. You know, they know that the labor market being too strong and being too hot can lead to more aggressive interest rate hikes. But at the same time, they're always going to say, look, more jobs being added, more paychecks going to Americans, that is essentially a good thing. And, you know, I don't have to tell you, the issue of the economy, the issue of inflation, those are some of the most important political issues for this White House and for Democrats heading into 2024. So, they're always going to sort of root for strength in the jobs market and they do basically feel like they have a good story to tell on the economy. But, again, inflation is the one sort of intractable problem that this president has faced, and they very much want to see that trend to continue in a downwards manner.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes, we'll see what President Biden says when he speaks out.MJ, Christine, thank you both so much for breaking down those massive, very hot jobs numbers today.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Now the Oscars. I thought it was last weekend, actually. I was confused.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Oh, come on.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I did. I was like, well, the Oscars are this weekend. It's this weekend, all right? The first since the infamous Chris Rock slap. How the shown plans to address last year's drama and some fresh controversy this year.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: OK, so I'm so out of it. I'm like, that's Lady Gaga? Lady Gaga up for another Academy Award this weekend. Will it be her second win for the best original song? This time for "Top GunStephanie Elam joins us now from Los Angeles to preview the ceremony. Stephanie, hey, how are you? I don't know, who's going to - who's going to get the big win?

utterances.speaker: STEPHANIE ELAM, CNN CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: I mean there's so many questions here. I mean, Don, we know that there has been plenty of drama in the Dolby Theatre when we've gone to Oscars. Of course, they would like for you to focus on the drama on the big screens. But just in case you forgot what happened last year, and what they're looking to fix this year, watch this.(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: And when we're done with this, we're going to be carpeting all of Hollywood.ELAM (voice over): The Oscars are back. The first since the slap made Hollywood's biggest night the Academy's biggest nightmare.

utterances.speaker: CHRIS ROCK, COMEDIAN
utterances.sentences: It still hurts!

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: Just a week after Chris Rock took aim at Will Smith --JIMMY KIMMEL, HOST, "JIMMY KIMMEL LIVE": The second I saw Will Smith get up out of his seat, I would have been halfway to the Wetzels (ph) Pretzel.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: All eyes will be on host Jimmy Kimmel, who says he will address the slap.

utterances.speaker: KIMMEL
utterances.sentences: You know, comedians are mad about it. It's one of those things that for a group of people that find everything funny, it's like not funny, you know. But, of course, it's, you know, you have to.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: The fallout also upends Oscar tradition since Smith won best actor last year.

utterances.speaker: MATTHEW BELLONI, FOUNDING PARTNER, PUCK
utterances.sentences: They have to find somebody to present best actress, because typically the tradition is, if you win best actor, you come back and you present best actress. But that's not going to happen because he's banned from the show.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: This year's drama should come from the awards. Possible upsets --

utterances.speaker: JAMIE LEE CURTIS, SUPPORTING ACTRESS NOMINEE
utterances.sentences: Well, I've been an actress since I was 19.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: A late SAG Awards surge from Jamie Lee Curtis could lift her over supporting actress favorite Angela Bassett. Neither veteran has ever won. ELAM (on camera)

utterances.speaker: BRENDAN FRASER, ACTOR
utterances.sentences: I'm smiling and breathing.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: SAG and Critics Choice winner Brendan Fraser will go down the wire with Austin Butler for best actor.

utterances.speaker: AUSTIN BUTLER, ACTOR
utterances.sentences: I'm ready. Ready to fly.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: The "Elvis" star won a BAFTA, the British Oscar, a bellwether since the Academy has welcomed more international voters.BAZLUHRMANN, DIRECTOR, "ELVIS": Denzel Washington said to me, you're about to work with a young actor, because he had just worked with him, whose work ethic is like no other. He was right.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: If there's an Oscar shocker, it could be for best actress, where Michelle Yeoh is expected to win for "Everything, Everywhere, All at Once."

utterances.speaker: KATE BLANCHETT, ACTRESS
utterances.sentences: I am excited. I'm excited.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: Kate Blanchett's BAFTA win keeps her competitive. But the outlier, Andrea Riseborough, whose role as an alcoholic in the small film "To Leslie" led to a social media push inside Hollywood that won her a surprise nomination. She was allowed to remain a contender after an Academy investigation into the tactics of the campaign. A probe that upset some of Riseborough's supporters.

utterances.speaker: BELLONI
utterances.sentences: There could be a protest vote that goes on here. And if there is a shocker on Oscar night, it's going to be if she wins.(END VIDEOTAPE)

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: OK, so in the spirit of the Academy Awards, the Oscars, Kaitlan and Stephanie, your picks for best picture?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Oh, Stephanie?

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: I've got to go - I've got to go with what I've seen, because I've been at all these awards shows.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Oh.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Oh, my gosh.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: I think "Everything, Everywhere, All at Once." Got to pull out.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: We picked the same thing.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes. ELAM

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: So - thank you.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: Don?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: No, it's backwards.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Oh, yes.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: I was like, no pick. Oh, that's dramatic.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: You know why?

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: That's very dramatic.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Here's why. It's the only one I've seen. I saw it on the plane as -- when I was going to the queen's funeral. It's the only one that I have seen.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: I picked this one because one of the directors is from Alabama. The two Daniels.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: And, he's amazing. And also Michelle Yeoh is awesome. So -

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: Also, I would just like to point out, we have some veteran actors who are up for winning big awards that they haven't won before.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: So, it could be a really thrilling night for some of our favorites that we all have loved over the decades to see if they win on the champagne carpet as they walk down it on Sunday evening.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Can I - I want to two things real quick. Humble brag, I've been texting with Courtney B. Vance. And, you know, we love the wife is amazing.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: You need to tell people who his wife is.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: You tell people who his wife is.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: Angela Bassett, who is up for "Wakanda Forever."

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: She's up for that role. So, she may win. Or it could be now Jamie Lee Curtis from "Everything, Everywhere, All at Once." We've seen that the -- for all season long it's been Angela Bassett. LEMON

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: But we saw at the SAG Awards that Jamie Lee Curtis won.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: So, we're not sure. But both of those actors very much loved in Hollywood.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: The last time we covered -- I don't know if it was the last time we covered, but the last Oscars that I actually attended in person, because (INAUDIBLE) would do the red carpet with you and then we'd do the after show, was 2016 when Chris Rock, fun fact, was the host. Interesting, right?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Oh, a long way (ph).

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: I don't think we can expect to see Chris Rock again. I don't think he will be there, at least this year.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes. You can see why.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Thanks, Steph.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thanks, Stephanie.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Good luck.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: We'll be watching.

utterances.speaker: ELAM
utterances.sentences: Thanks.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: All right, the Oscars is not the only thing this weekend. Daylight Savings is going to make your Sunday scary -- a little scarier this Sunday, as you're watching the Oscars. Harry Enten is going to explain why this morning's number is 65.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: He's going to be on the red carpet.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Well, you won't -

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: One of my all-time favorites. I love Cher.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Well, don't play this weekend because you're not actually going to be turning back the time. Instead, you're going to be turning it forward, because the clocks are going forward. Daylight Savings time is this Sunday, which means you're going to lose an hour of sleep, but for the next couple of months you'll have an extra hour of daylight, so it's totally worth it.This, of course, has been a big debate on Capitol Hill. Republican Senator Marco Rubio has reintroduced a bill that would make Daylight Savings Time permanent nationwide, which mean no more - it would mean no more changing back the clocks. But the question is, is that what people want? Is that what the Americans want? Harry Enten has looked into this for us and has this morning's number. Harry, what is it? Do people - do people want this to be something that is actually passed by Congress?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: How (ph)?

utterances.speaker: HARRY ENTEN, CNN SENIOR DATA REPORTER
utterances.sentences: Yes. So, this morning's number is 65. Sixty-five percent of Americans who dislike changing the clocks twice a year. I can tell you, I am certainly one of them. I am not at all looking forward to losing an hour of sleep this weekend. It means one extra less hour of sleep and it also means the weekend has one less hour in it.But here is the issue, Kaitlan. Here is the issue. We can't agree on a solution. So, Americans don't like changing the clocks, but they can't agree on a solution. Look, 38 percent want Daylight Saving Time, no "s," all year-round, 26 percent want standard time all year-round and then there's 32 percent who like the current system, which is a minority. But the fact is, you've got 38 percent who like Daylight Saving Time all year-round, and standard time, 26 percent. So the people who dislike changing their clocks, they can't actually agree on a solution.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Interesting. I thought there was -- I thought we were -- it was going to be permanent, but maybe that was -- I'm dreaming. I don't know.So, then what about Daylight Saving Time year-round? Do you -- I mean, I kind of like it. I like Daylight Saving all year. And, you're right, leave off the last "s" for Saving.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Harry, say that again. If it is permanent, that's when it doesn't rise in Grand Rapids until 9

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Correct. If we do in fact make Daylight Saving Time year-round permanent, what we would find is in Grand Rapids, Michigan, in January, the sun wouldn't rise until after 9

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: No, I don't like that.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I don't know. I just -- I just -

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: We're in studio anyway.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I'm still thinking about it. I can't get over the fact that especially us on this shift we're going to lose an hour of sleep.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: I feel for you.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Harry Enten.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: You're on this shift, too, Harry.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Yes, I know.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Harry Enten, thank you.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Thank you.
